"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, today I'm building a new compost pile, but first I have to get the old compost out of here. So I've been wheelbarrowing it out. There used to be three big mounds over this whole area, and now there's just uh a little bit of scattering. Um the last thing I do before I move it is I let the chickens in, and they flatten my piles and they spread it out all over, and then I just put it in the wheelbarrow and throw it over there. It's just a good way of breaking it up before I do that. Sometimes I do, sometimes I don't. This time I did, and as you can see, everything's been scattered pretty well. I've ranked it up over into here, and I'm shoveling it into this wheelbarrow. I've done probably about 30 wheelbarrows, uh, and I'm taking it over to my worm pile where it will cure for several months until uh spring, and it's just now December. So we'll have like uh three months of curing where the worms will do all the damage. But this is really interesting. We've had like an unreal amount of rain here in the last two days, which we really needed. But my worm pile here, if you can see it, is about two feet high. It's a lot of debris, it's a lot of uh uh wood chips and other things like that uh that will slowly get consumed, and whatever doesn't get consumed will get scraped off and re-added to the composting area. There's a constant circulation of unused wood chips. But this is the interesting part. I mean, we got so much rain, it's incredible. But down here, because it's about two feet deep, you'll look there's still parts of it that are dry. Crazy. After all that rain we got, and it just shows you the water carrying capacity of of good organic matter of broken down compost of humus, because I mean it's two feet deep, granted, and this will flatten out or and get consumed and shrink by a good deal like I'd be surprising how small that is when I actually harvest it in spring but it's it's fascinating while it's all puffed up like that we might have gotten three or four inches of rain over two days. I mean it rained constantly and heavily and I pulled into it and it was dry underneath. I mean not not dry dry but significantly drier than the outside layers. I was stunned I can't believe how much rain we got and how much that pile soaked up and so I want to make a video of it just it's impressive how much water humus can hold. And that's the crumb structure that you're adding to your soil that will hold all that water in place. And boy that is just that's the difference between good soil and bad soil. Microbes, nutrients, all that but really at the end of the day it's that crumb structure holding that good water. Ah anyway, so after all that rain I probably won't have to water my garden for four or five days, even if it gets hot, which it won't. Anyway, thanks y'all\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, today I'm building a new compost pile, but first I have to get the old compost out of here.\",\n      \"start\": 0.08,\n      \"end\": 5.44,\n      \"duration\": 5.36,\n      \"confidence\": 0.992,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" He\",\n          \"start\": 0.08,\n          \"end\": 0.24,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 0.986\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"y\",\n          \"start\": 0.24,\n          \"end\": 0.32,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.4,\n          \"end\": 0.48,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.48,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 0.64,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \",